When this rule is mentioned use this documentation:

# Triggers

Triggers are a special kind of operation that are used to poll for changes in a SaaS. They are used to implement the 
source part of a flow. Triggers are different from operations in that they are not invoked directly by the user, but 
instead are invoked by the platform when it needs to check for changes in the SaaS.

## Trigger extraction strategy

The trigger extraction strategy is the way the trigger will be used to extract data from the SaaS. The strategy is 
defined by the `@TriggerStrategy` annotation. The strategy can be one of the following:

- `@TriggerStrategy(Watermark)`: The trigger will use a watermark to track the last time it was invoked. The watermark 
  is a value that is stored in the platform and is used to determine what data has already been processed. The watermark 
  is typically a timestamp, but it can be any value that can be used to determine what data has already been processed.

- `@TriggerStrategy(Polling)`: The trigger will be invoked periodically to check for changes in the SaaS. The polling 
  interval is defined by the platform.

- `@TriggerStrategy(Webhook)`: The trigger will be invoked when a webhook is received from the SaaS. The webhook URL is 
  defined by the platform.

## Input mapper

The input mapper is a function that is used to transform the input of the trigger into the format expected by the SaaS. 
The input mapper is defined by the `@InputMapper` annotation. The input mapper is optional, but it is recommended to use 
it to ensure that the input is in the correct format.

## Initial watermark

The initial watermark is the value that will be used as the watermark when the trigger is first invoked. The initial 
watermark is defined by the `@InitialWatermark` annotation. The initial watermark is optional, but it is recommended to 
use it to ensure that the trigger starts from a known point in time.

## Example

The following example shows how to define a trigger that uses a watermark to track the last time it was invoked:

```
@OperationElement()
var trigger : Operation<TriggerInputType, TriggerOutputType, ResultFailure<GenericErrorResult, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "trigger",
    displayName: "Trigger",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({
            method: 'GET',
            path: "/trigger?since=" ++ parameter.since
        })
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response.body as TriggerOutputType)
        else
          failure(response.body as GenericErrorResult)
    }
}

type TriggerInputType = {
    since: @InitialWatermark() String
}

type TriggerOutputType = {
    events: Array<Event>
}

type Event = {
    id: String,
    timestamp: String,
    data: Object
}
